(7, 'david@gmail.com', '2026-01-30 16:15:11', 'govtech', 'TrustVote Lab: Secure Pilots for Digital Voting Research', 'TrustVote Lab is a research-driven GovTech initiative that conducts secure, transparent, non-binding pilots and independent audits of digital voting systems to produce empirical evidence on security,', '', '', '', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/DEMOCRACY/Democracy_TrustVoteLab_Canvas.pdf', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/DEMOCRACY/Democracy_TrustVoteLab_Executive_Summary.pdf', 'TrustVote Lab\nRecommended length: ~85–90 seconds\nTone: Careful, transparent, research-driven\n1. Opening & Personal Introduction (5–10s)\nHello, my name is [Name], and I’m part of the research team behind TrustVote Lab.\n2. Project Definition (10–15s)\nTrustVote Lab is a research-oriented GovTech initiative that pilots digital voting technologies in\ncontrolled, non-binding contexts to better understand their risks, limits, and potential.\n3. Problem Statement (15–20s)\nDigital voting raises critical questions about security, trust, accessibility, and democratic legitimacy.\nYet meaningful experimentation is difficult—because testing these systems directly in political\nelections carries unacceptable risks.\nAs a result, public debate often relies on assumptions rather than evidence.\n4. Solution Explanation (15–20s)\nTrustVote Lab creates safe pilot environments for digital voting research.\nWe conduct simulations and internal-use pilots—such as organizational elections or participatory\nbudgeting exercises—under strict oversight, independent audits, and open documentation.\nEvery pilot is designed to test not only what works, but also what doesn’t.\n5. Key Innovation / Differentiator (15–20s)\nThe key innovation is our explicit non-deployment stance.\nTrustVote Lab does not offer a voting product. Instead, it provides a transparent research framework\nthat prioritizes caution, public reporting of limitations, and democratic responsibility.\n6. Target Audience (10–15s)\nTrustVote Lab is designed for universities, research institutes, electoral experts, and public\ninstitutions seeking evidence-based insight into digital voting—without risking democratic\nprocesses.\n7. Vision / Impact Statement (5–10s)\nTrustVote Lab is not about digitizing elections—it’s about building trustworthy knowledge before\ndecisions are made, and ensuring that democratic innovation is guided by evidence, not hype.\n8. Closing (3–5s)\nThank you.', 'TrustVote Lab is a research-oriented GovTech initiative focused on piloting secure digital voting technologies in low-risk contexts such as internal organizational elections, participatory budgeting simulations, or academic research.<p>\nThe project explicitly avoids deployment in binding political elections. Its goal is to test usability, accessibility, and security assumptions under controlled conditions. All pilots are conducted with independent audits, open documentation, and public reporting of limitations and risks.<p>\nTrustVote Lab operates in partnership with universities, research institutes, and electoral experts. Funding comes from research grants and institutional partnerships. The project positions itself as a contribution to democratic research, not as a ready-made solution. Transparency, caution, and public oversight are core principles.', 81, '{\"score\": 81, \"evaluation\": \"Rubric summary (each criterion scored out of 4): 1) Identified Public Problem: 4/4 — Clearly defined need for safe, non-binding research environments to evaluate digital voting. 2) Contribution to Democracy & Common Good: 4/4 — Prioritizes transparency, independent audits, accessibility and evidence for public debate. 3) Institutional Design & Fit: 3/4 — Good alignment with research institutions and public actors, but institutional adoption path and integration details are under-specified. 4) Ethics, Digital Rights & Data Protection: 3/4 — Strong emphasis on ethics, audits and non-deployment; lacks concrete data protection procedures and privacy protocols. 5) Technical Viability & Security: 3/4 — Security-aware design (cryptography, audits) but no detailed architecture, threat model, or resilience plans provided. 6) Economic Sustainability Model: 3/4 — Clear grant- and partnership-based model; medium-term funding continuity is a gap. 7) Scalability, Replicability & Governance: 3/4 — Responsible, research-first scaling noted but governance and cross-context adaptation need clearer mechanisms. 8) Team & Project Legitimacy: 3/4 — Multidisciplinary team described, but composition and institutional affiliations are still generic/undeveloped. Overall assessment: A viable, democratically responsible GovTech research initiative with solid principles and clear public value; success depends on strengthening institutional partnerships, funding stability, and operational details (security, privacy, governance).\", \"strengths\": [\"Clear, well-defined public problem: need for safe, non-binding environments to test digital voting.\", \"Strong democratic orientation: explicit non-deployment stance, transparency, independent audits, and open reporting.\", \"Multidisciplinary approach combining security, legal, political science, and accessibility expertise.\", \"Research-first value proposition that reduces risk of premature adoption and contributes empirical evidence.\", \"Target stakeholders and channels are appropriate (universities, electoral researchers, public administrations).\"], \"weaknesses\": [\"Team and institutional ownership are underspecified (’GovTech Research Consortium’ not yet defined), limiting credibility for partners.\", \"Lack of concrete technical architecture, attacker threat model, and resilience plans for pilot systems.\", \"Data protection and privacy procedures are not detailed (consent, minimization, retention, anonymization).\", \"Economic sustainability relies on project-based grants with identified funding continuity risk.\", \"Governance and operational processes for cross-jurisdictional replication and democratic oversight are high-level rather than operationalized.\"], \"recommendations\": [\"Define and publish a formal governance charter including participant roles, oversight bodies (including civil society and electoral authorities), decision-making processes, and conflict-of-interest policies.\", \"Develop and publish detailed technical documentation: reference architecture, threat model, security controls, logging/forensics plan, and procedures for simulated failure modes and responsible disclosure.\", \"Create a comprehensive data protection and privacy framework: data minimization, consent flows, pseudonymization/aggregation methods, retention policies, and third-party audit clauses.\", \"Secure multi-year seed funding or institutional anchor partners to cover baseline operational costs and reduce dependency on short-term grants.\", \"Pilot an initial demonstrator with a named university or public partner and independent auditor; publish complete methodology, raw (appropriately anonymized) datasets, and full audit reports to build credibility.\", \"Establish a sustainability plan that diversifies funding (grants, commissioned evaluations, institutional subscriptions) while preserving non-commercial, public-interest orientation.\", \"Develop a replication toolkit and onboarding process for partner institutions: templates for ethical approval, technical deployment checklists, and governance MOUs to support responsible scaling.\", \"Communicate clearly to the public and officials the limits of pilots vs. binding elections, and publish plain-language summaries to foster democratic trust and uptake of findings.\"]}', '', '', '[{\"title\": \"OpenCouncil: Transparent Decision Tracking for Local Governments\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both projects are civic-tech initiatives aimed at strengthening democratic institutions through transparency, integrity, and public trust; both target public-sector actors and emphasize accessibility and legal/compliance alignment.\", \"differences\": [\"Core purpose: TrustVote Lab focuses on research-oriented, non-binding pilots of digital voting technologies; OpenCouncil focuses on publication and traceability of council decisions (agenda ? vote ? implementation).\", \"Business model: TrustVote Lab is grant-funded, research-first and non-commercial; OpenCouncil is a B2G SaaS subscription product with recurring revenue.\", \"Technical integration: OpenCouncil emphasizes integration with municipal administrative workflows and long-term operational use; TrustVote Lab emphasizes short-term controlled pilot environments, independent audits, and explicit exclusion of binding elections.\", \"Outcome orientation: OpenCouncil delivers continuous public records and operational transparency; TrustVote Lab produces empirical research, audits, and public reports about technology risks and limits.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use OpenCouncil as a public-facing channel to publish structured, traceable reports and decision timelines for TrustVote Lab pilots to increase transparency and institutional uptake.\", \"Co-design documentation standards so pilot findings are integrated into municipal workflows and legal/regulatory analyses hosted by OpenCouncil.\", \"Run joint pilot projects where TrustVote Lab evaluates voting-related metadata and OpenCouncil demonstrates how non-binding pilot outcomes inform decision-tracking and policy updates.\"]}, {\"title\": \"CivicPulse: Inclusive Digital Consultations for Public Policy Design\", \"match\": 65, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritize inclusive, ethically governed digital democratic processes, accessibility, transparency, and institutional legitimacy; both are aimed at public administrations and civil-society stakeholders and emphasize moderation/governance principles.\", \"differences\": [\"Core functionality: TrustVote Lab provides secure, non-binding pilots and security/