(24, 'dorothy@gmail.com', '2026-01-30 20:58:09', 'sustainability', 'EnergySense Communities: Collective Energy Efficiency for Apartment Buildings', 'A privacy-first platform that aggregates and anonymizes smart-meter data to enable community-driven energy-saving challenges and measurable building-level reductions in energy use and emissions for ap', 'Dorothy', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K5NgaIyiAEY', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/SUSTAINABILITY/Sustainability_EnergySenseCommunities_Canvas.pdf', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/SUSTAINABILITY/Sustainability_EnergySenseCommunities_Executive_Summary.pdf', 'Recommended length: ~80 seconds\nTone: Transparent, collaborative, climate-focused\n1. Opening & Personal Introduction (5–8s)\nHello, my name is Alex, and I’m part of the team behind EnergySense Communities.\n2. Project Definition (10–12s)\nEnergySense Communities is a platform that helps residents of apartment buildings collectively\nreduce energy consumption through shared insights and community action.\n3. Problem Statement (15–18s)\nApartment buildings consume a large share of urban energy, yet residents often lack visibility into\nhow their building performs as a whole.\nMost solutions rely on individual monitoring or expensive upgrades, raising privacy concerns and\nfinancial barriers.\n4. Solution Explanation (15–18s)\nEnergySense Communities combines smart meter data, shared dashboards, and building-level\nchallenges to encourage behavioral change.\nAll insights are aggregated and anonymized, focusing on collective progress rather than individual\nsurveillance.\n5. Key Innovation / Differentiator (15–18s)\nThe key innovation of EnergySense Communities is its community-first, privacy-preserving design.\nBy making energy use visible at the building level and linking it to collective goals, the platform\nenables measurable savings without major upfront investment.\n6. Target Audience (10–12s)\nEnergySense Communities is designed for housing cooperatives, property managers, and\nmunicipalities committed to accessible climate action.\n7. Vision / Impact Statement (5–8s)\nEnergySense Communities is not just about saving energy—it’s about empowering communities to\nact together on climate goals.\n8. Closing (3–5s)\nThank you.', 'EnergySense Communities is a platform that helps residents of apartment buildings collectively reduce energy consumption. The solution combines smart meters, shared dashboards, and community-based challenges that encourage behavioral change rather than relying solely on technological upgrades.<p>\nResidents receive aggregated, anonymized insights about energy use trends in their building, along with practical recommendations adapted to the local climate and building characteristics. The platform emphasizes transparency and avoids individual surveillance, focusing instead on collective progress and learning.<p>\nEnergySense works with housing cooperatives, property managers, and municipalities under a B2B/B2G model. Environmental impact is measured through verified reductions in energy consumption and CO? emissions at the building level. The goal is to make energy efficiency accessible and scalable without requiring large upfront investments.', 75, '{\"score\": 75, \"evaluation\": \"Per-criterion scores (0–4): 1) Identified Environmental Problem & Urgency: 4 — Clear, well-contextualized problem (apartment building energy waste; rising costs; policy relevance). 2) Sustainability & Circular Economy Approach: 3 — Coherent sustainability and waste-prevention via behavioral change but limited explicit circular-economy measures (reuse/recycling/regeneration). 3) Real & Measurable Environmental Impact: 3 — Platform claims building-level tracking and verified reductions, but no detailed metrics, baselines, or measurement methodology provided. 4) Alignment Between Environmental Impact & Business Model: 4 — B2B/B2G subscription model aligns incentives with building-level savings and recurring engagement. 5) Technical & Operational Feasibility: 3 — Technically plausible (smart meter integration, anonymization) but depends on data access agreements and proven resident engagement. 6) Regulatory Compliance & ESG Framework: 2 — Privacy-first intent noted, but regulatory strategy, standards, and certifications are not detailed. 7) Environmental Scalability & Replicability: 3 — High software-driven scalability potential; risks from data access variability and engagement retention. 8) Team & Green Execution Capacity: 2 — Roles and expertise areas are identified, but the team is pre-MVP with no named credentials or track record. Aggregate: 24/32 ? Final score: 75/100.\", \"strengths\": [\"Clear, relevant environmental problem focused on multi?family building energy waste.\", \"Privacy-first, non?surveillance design increases trust and adoption potential.\", \"Collective, community-driven approach leverages social motivation rather than costly retrofits.\", \"Low upfront infrastructure requirements and a software-driven model enable scalable deployment.\", \"Business model (B2B/B2G subscriptions) aligns revenue with building-level impact and institutional clients.\"], \"weaknesses\": [\"Limited explicit circular-economy features (no reuse/recycling/regeneration pathways described).\", \"Lack of detailed measurement methodology, baselines, normalization procedures, and quantified impact estimates.\", \"Regulatory and compliance planning is superficial — no mention of specific laws, certifications, or ESG frameworks.\", \"High dependency on access to smart meter/utility data and on sustained resident engagement.\", \"Team composition is described only at a role level; no named experts or evidence of execution track record provided.\"], \"recommendations\": [\"Run a structured pilot with a municipal or housing cooperative partner to secure smart?meter access and demonstrate real savings and engagement metrics.\", \"Define and publish a measurement protocol: baseline definition, normalization (weather, occupancy), KPIs (kWh saved, % reduction, CO? avoided), verification cadence, and data transparency practices.\", \"Develop a regulatory & data?protection plan (e.g., GDPR/sectoral rules), pursue relevant certifications/standards, and document privacy/security controls to reduce legal and adoption risks.\", \"Strengthen the team and advisory board with named hires/advisors experienced in building energy programs, utility partnerships, and community engagement.\", \"Add circularity extensions where possible (e.g., linking savings to reinvestment in low?carbon building upgrades, coordinated appliance replacement programs, or material?reuse initiatives) to broaden environmental impact.\", \"Design retention and engagement mechanisms (automated nudges, building-level rewards, integration into property management workflows) and measure behavioral decay to sustain long?term savings.\"]}', '', '', '[{\"title\": \"ReLoop Materials: Circular Packaging for Local Food Producers\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both are early-stage, B2B/B2G sustainability services that combine a physical service or platform with digital tracking and reporting, sell recurring subscriptions to institutional clients, aim for measurable environmental impact, and rely on partner networks (cooperatives, distributors, municipalities) and pilots to scale.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector and beneficiaries differ: EnergySense targets multi?family housing and residents; ReLoop targets small and medium local food producers and distributors.\", \"Core offering differs: EnergySense is a software-driven energy aggregation and community engagement platform; ReLoop is a physical circular packaging service with logistics, cleaning, and container assets plus tracking.\", \"Technology and infrastructure needs: EnergySense depends on smart?meter data integration and anonymization (low upfront physical capital); ReLoop requires capital for durable containers, cleaning facilities, and route logistics (high upfront capex and operational complexity).\", \"Engagement model differs: EnergySense emphasizes collective behavior change and community challenges among residents; ReLoop embeds reuse into operational workflows and logistics for producers.\", \"Key operational risks differ: EnergySense’s risks center on data access and sustained resident engagement; ReLoop’s risks center on logistics efficiency, route density, and container lifecycle management.\", \"Impact metrics differ: EnergySense measures building?level energy and emissions reductions; ReLoop measures reuse cycles, waste avoided, and container turnover.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share platform design and metrics/reporting lessons (e.g., anonymized aggregated dashboards and verified impact tracking) to strengthen each other’s monitoring modules.\", \"Pilot a joint municipal program in housing cooperatives where ReLoop provides reusable packaging for communal kitchens and EnergySense reports combined building sustainability impacts to municipalities.\", \"Co-develop B2B/B2G sales materials and municipal partnerships that bundle waste prevention and building energy reduction as a single institutional offering.\", \"Exchange community engagement techniques: adapt EnergySense’s collective challenge mechanics to increase producer/consumer reuse adoption in ReLoop pilots.\", \"Coordinate on privacy and data governance approaches for combined operational data (logistics tracking + building energy) to build resident and producer trust.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SoilBack: Regenerative Practices for Small-Scale Agriculture\", \"match\": 70, \"similarities\": \"Both are early-stage service platforms focused on behavior/practice change rather than capital-intensive retrofit or financialized offset solutions; both target institutional and community partners (cooperatives, networks), use digital tools for guidance and monitoring, offer subscription/partnership revenue models, emphasize measurable environmental outcomes, and rely on peer/collective learning and long?term advisory or engagement relationships.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain and beneficiaries differ: EnergySense focuses on multi?family residential energy use and residents/property managers; SoilBack focuses on small-scale farmers and agronomic practice change.\", \"Core functionality differs: EnergySense aggregates smart?meter energy data and runs collective challenges; SoilBack delivers tailored agronomic guidance, field demonstrations, and tracks soil/soil-health indicators.\", \"Technology and data types differ: EnergySense depends on meter integration, anonymization and building-level analytics; SoilBack uses field data, practice tracking and soil indicator monitoring (often qualitative or periodic measurements).\", \"Engagement and delivery differ: EnergySense uses resident-facing dashboards and community engagement cycles inside buildings; SoilBack uses peer learning circles, on?farm advisory, and region-specific adaptation.\", \"Scalability constraints differ: EnergySense’s scaling depends on data access agreements and resident engagement persistence; SoilBack’s scaling depends on agronomic advisory capacity and regional adaptation expertise.\", \"Impact metrics and time horizons differ: EnergySense reports energy and CO2 reductions at building scale relatively quickly; SoilBack focuses on gradual soil-health improvements and longer-term resilience gains.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange community engagement and retention practices (e.g., collective challenges, peer learning formats) to improve adoption and sustained behavior change in each context.\", \"Adapt EnergySense’s aggregated, privacy?preserving dashboard design to present regional farm progress anonymously for SoilBack’s cooperative reporting needs.\", \"Co-create pilot projects in urban/regional contexts (e.g., housing cooperatives with community gardens or urban farms) to trial combined energy, food and soil resilience interventions and shared impact reporting.\", \"Pursue joint funding or municipal partnership proposals that bundle building energy efficiency and local regenerative agriculture as integrated climate resilience programs.\", \"Share monitoring and verification approaches to align short?term behavioral indicators (energy use, practice adoption) with longer?term environmental metrics, improving cross-sector impact narratives.\"]}]', '[{\"title\": \"MindAnchor: Evidence-Based Mental Health Support for Young Adults\", \"match\": 28, \"similarities\": \"Both are digital behaviour-change platforms with privacy-first design, emphasise ethical boundaries, use SaaS delivery models, and depend on evidence-informed engagement to influence user practices.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: MindAnchor focuses on mental wellbeing for individuals (young adults); EnergySense targets building-level energy reduction in apartment communities.\", \"Primary user: MindAnchor is consumer-facing (individuals/institutions like universities); EnergySense targets housing cooperatives, property managers and municipalities.\", \"Data inputs: MindAnchor relies on self-report and program engagement; EnergySense depends on smart-meter energy data and building-level analytics.\", \"Outcome metrics: MindAnchor measures emotional regulation and resilience; EnergySense measures energy consumption and CO? reductions.\", \"Service model: MindAnchor includes optional paid professional sessions and freemium tiers; EnergySense is B2B/B2G subscription per building.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share behavioural-engagement design patterns (e.g., micro-modules, habit formation) to improve resident participation and lasting energy behaviour change.\", \"Co-develop privacy-first consent and onboarding flows that accommodate sensitive personal data across both domains.\", \"Run cross-sector trials to study how mental-wellbeing interventions (stress management) affect residents\' energy-use behaviour (e.g., thermal comfort choices).\"]}, {\"title\": \"CareLink Home: Coordinated Support for Elderly People Living Alone\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasise privacy-first, non-surveillance design, human-in-the-loop alerting, multi-stakeholder dashboards, municipal partnerships, and ethical data handling to enable collective or coordinated support.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: CareLink Home targets individual safety/health and elderly care; EnergySense targets energy consumption and climate impact in buildings.\", \"Data types: CareLink uses sensor/activity-pattern signals and optional IoT; EnergySense uses aggregated smart-meter energy data.\", \"Intervention model: CareLink triggers human follow-up on anomalies; EnergySense runs collective challenges and behaviour-change campaigns.\", \"End beneficiaries: CareLink’s core beneficiaries are vulnerable individuals and caregivers; EnergySense’s beneficiaries are resident communities and building operators.\", \"Hardware reliance: CareLink explicitly integrates optional home sensors; EnergySense minimizes upfront infrastructure needs by using existing meters.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange anonymization and pattern-detection techniques to improve privacy-preserving aggregation for both activity and energy signals.\", \"Pilot joint municipal programs where energy dashboards are integrated into broader wellbeing services for building residents (e.g., combined safety and energy awareness campaigns).\", \"Share community engagement and human-in-the-loop response workflows to balance automated detection with respectful human follow-up.\"]}, {\"title\": \"MoveWell Rehab: Personalized Physical Rehabilitation for Chronic Conditions\", \"match\": 35, \"similarities\": \"Both use digital platforms to drive sustained behaviour change, rely on professional partners to validate content (physiotherapists / sustainability experts), and aim for measurable outcome improvements through ongoing engagement and tracking.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: MoveWell addresses individual health rehabilitation; EnergySense addresses collective energy efficiency.\", \"Personalisation: MoveWell provides individualized exercise plans; EnergySense focuses on building-level aggregated insights, not individual scoring.\", \"Regulatory/context: MoveWell aligns closely with clinical/professional care boundaries; EnergySense aligns with municipal energy policy and utilities.\", \"User interaction model: MoveWell includes remote professional adjustments; EnergySense coordinates communities through collective challenges and building dashboards.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share techniques for improving long-term adherence (reminders, progress tracking, motivational design) to increase resident engagement in energy programmes.\", \"Test integrations where MoveWell-style nudges are used in common-area facilities (e.g., stair use, communal heating behaviours) to study cross-domain behaviour change.\", \"Exchange outcome-measurement frameworks to strengthen validation methods for claimed impacts (adherence vs energy reductions).\"]}, {\"title\": \"PathLearn: Personalized Learning Pathways for Secondary Education\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS platforms that emphasise human-in-the-loop adaptivity, teacher/manager control over automated suggestions, and embedding the tool into existing institutional workflows (schools / building operations).\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: PathLearn is education-focused for secondary schools; EnergySense is an energy and community engagement platform for residential buildings.\", \"Decision-makers: PathLearn’s primary decision-makers are school leadership and curriculum coordinators; EnergySense’s are property managers, cooperative boards, and municipal energy officers.\", \"Core metrics: PathLearn measures learning outcomes and mastery progression; EnergySense measures energy consumption and emission reductions.\", \"User base: PathLearn serves teachers and students; EnergySense serves residents and building operators.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange teacher-in-the-loop / manager-in-the-loop design principles to ensure automated recommendations remain interpretable and accepted by institutional decision-makers.\", \"Share approaches to onboarding and long-term retention in institutional contexts to reduce dropout and ensure continuous use.\", \"Collaborate on cross-sector pilots in student housing where educational campaigns could be coupled with building-level energy challenges.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SkillBridge: Practice-Based Digital Training for Workforce Reskilling\", \"match\": 25, \"similarities\": \"Both are digital platforms delivering outcome-oriented interventions, rely on partnerships (industry/professional) for content validity, and pursue measurable impact tied to user behaviour (skills gained / energy saved).\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: SkillBridge targets adult reskilling and employment outcomes; EnergySense targets energy efficiency and environmental impact in residential buildings.\", \"Pedagogy: SkillBridge emphasises experiential, competency-based learning; EnergySense focuses on community challenges and behavioural nudges rather than formal training.\", \"Customers: SkillBridge sells to enterprises and public training programs; EnergySense targets housing cooperatives and municipalities.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Provide training modules for building managers and resident champions on running energy-efficiency challenges, using SkillBridge’s practice-first approach.\", \"Co-design competency frameworks for community energy coordinators to professionalise the role of resident facilitators.\", \"Share assessment/reporting techniques to demonstrate measurable outcomes to institutional purchasers (municipalities, cooperatives).\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReadTogether: Inclusive Literacy Support for Early Learners\", \"match\": 20, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasise pedagogy/behavioural engagement over intrusive metrics, prioritise low-complexity, privacy-aware user experiences, and target institutional adoption (schools / cooperatives/municipalities).\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: ReadTogether is early literacy; EnergySense focuses on energy usage and climate impact.\", \"User groups: ReadTogether serves children, families and teachers; EnergySense serves adult residents, property managers, and municipalities.\", \"Interaction model: ReadTogether integrates offline family activities and audio storytelling; EnergySense integrates with smart-meter data and building dashboards.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Borrow ReadTogether’s family- and community-engagement techniques to design inclusive, low-pressure communication campaigns for residents (e.g., household activities tied to energy savings).\", \"Share privacy-preserving design practices for vulnerable user groups to inform resident-facing features.\", \"Explore co-created neighbourhood education events that combine literacy and sustainability themes to deepen community ties.\"]}, {\"title\": \"LocalHands: Community-Based Support for Informal Caregivers\", \"match\": 60, \"similarities\": \"Both centre local community networks, partner with municipalities and NGOs, emphasise dignity and non-surveillance approaches, use digital platforms plus local facilitation, and aim for social impact through strengthened local coordination.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain focus: LocalHands targets informal caregiving and wellbeing; EnergySense targets collective energy efficiency and emissions reductions.\", \"Primary beneficiaries: Caregivers and care recipients vs building residents and building operators.\", \"Service delivery: LocalHands leans on facilitation and peer networks; EnergySense focuses on data-driven dashboards and collective energy challenges.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Co-develop community facilitation toolkits that combine caregiving mutual aid and energy-saving actions (e.g., neighbourhood support events that also promote energy literacy).\", \"Share methodologies for sustaining long-term community engagement and facilitator training.\", \"Partner on municipal pilots where social support networks help amplify energy behaviour-change campaigns, leveraging LocalHands’ facilitator networks.\"]}, {\"title\": \"AccessPath: Inclusive Employment Pathways for People with Disabilities\", \"match\": 35, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasise co-design, person-centred approaches, partnerships with public agencies and NGOs, and measurable social impact through institutional contracts (B2B/B2G).\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: AccessPath addresses employment inclusion for people with disabilities; EnergySense addresses energy use and building-level climate action.\", \"User agency: AccessPath places people with disabilities centrally in co-design of roles; EnergySense focuses on aggregated, anonymized building-level insights rather than individual profiling.\", \"Operational model: AccessPath provides advisory and co-design services; EnergySense provides a data/engagement platform integrated with meters.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Co-create inclusive engagement materials and accessibility-first dashboards so energy tools are usable by residents with diverse needs.\", \"Pilot inclusive energy programmes with AccessPath partners to ensure equitable participation in building-level challenges.\", \"Exchange co-design practices to ensure resident voice, especially from underrepresented groups, is embedded in EnergySense interventions.\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReLoop Materials: Circular Packaging for Local Food Producers\", \"match\": 48, \"similarities\": \"Both are sustainability-focused, B2B/B2G service models that integrate physical systems with digital tracking, emphasise prevention/avoidance (reuse vs behaviour change), rely on partner networks, and provide measurable environmental impact reporting.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector: ReLoop focuses on reusable packaging logistics for food producers; EnergySense focuses on residential energy consumption behaviour and smart-meter data.\", \"Operational model: ReLoop manages containers, cleaning and logistics; EnergySense manages data aggregation, dashboards and community engagement.\", \"Hardware: ReLoop requires physical container inventory and sanitation operations; EnergySense relies primarily on existing metering infrastructure.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share lifecycle-tracking and environmental reporting best practices (reuse cycles vs energy savings) to improve impact verification methods.\", \"Pilot combined sustainability programmes in housing-cooperative cafeterias or shared kitchens using ReLoop containers with EnergySense community engagement to promote low-waste, low-energy practices.\", \"Coordinate with municipal partners to bundle circular packaging and building energy-efficiency incentives under local sustainability programmes.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SoilBack: Regenerative Practices for Small-Scale Agriculture\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both promote practical, practice-focused sustainability (behaviour/practice change rather than offsets), use advisory and peer-learning models, and emphasise transparent, field-based indicators and partnerships with cooperatives and local institutions.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector: SoilBack serves small-scale farmers and agronomy practices; EnergySense serves urban apartment buildings and residents.\", \"Data types: SoilBack tracks agronomic indicators; EnergySense uses energy consumption and smart-meter data.\", \"Delivery: SoilBack provides agronomic guidance and peer learning; EnergySense provides aggregated dashboards and community challenges.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange methodologies for peer-learning circles and cooperative outreach to improve resident engagement strategies.\", \"Share approaches to modest-cost interventions and phased adoption to ensure farmer/building-level feasibility and persistence.\", \"Collaborate on municipal sustainability programmes that link building-level energy actions to urban food/green-space initiatives supported by SoilBack.\"]}, {\"title\": \"FlowOps: Workflow Automation for Small Professional Services Firms\", \"match\": 42, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS products focused on simplifying institutional workflows, provide no-code or low-friction integrations, emphasise embedding into daily operations to achieve durable impact, and target SMEs/institutions as primary buyers.\", \"differences\": [\"Functional focus: FlowOps provides workflow automation templates for professional services; EnergySense provides energy analytics and community engagement for buildings.\", \"User base: FlowOps targets small firms (law, accounting); EnergySense targets property managers, cooperatives and municipal programmes.\", \"Tech integrations: FlowOps integrates with productivity and storage tools; EnergySense integrates with smart-meters and utility data sources.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Leverage FlowOps’ template-driven onboarding and automation patterns to streamline building onboarding, reporting workflows, and municipal contract fulfilment for EnergySense deployments.\", \"Integrate EnergySense reporting with professional services workflows (e.g., property management operations) to reduce manual reporting burden.\", \"Share best practices on low-friction SaaS adoption for non-technical institutional users.\"]}, {\"title\": \"InsightPulse: Customer Feedback Analytics for Product Teams\", \"match\": 44, \"similarities\": \"Both rely on aggregating diverse data streams into actionable insights, emphasise human-in-the-loop synthesis rather than opaque automation, provide traceability from insights to actions, and target teams that make operational decisions based on analytics dashboards.\", \"differences\": [\"Data focus: InsightPulse analyses qualitative customer feedback using NLP; EnergySense analyses quantitative energy consumption data and behavioural indicators.\", \"Primary customers: InsightPulse targets product teams in tech companies; EnergySense targets housing cooperatives, property managers and municipalities.\", \"Outputs: InsightPulse links feedback to product roadmaps; EnergySense links building energy trends to community challenges and recommended actions.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Adapt InsightPulse’s traceability and decision-linking patterns so EnergySense can better connect insights (e.g., peak consumption drivers) to specific community actions and operational decisions.\", \"Share human-in-the-loop synthesis workflows to ensure energy insights remain interpretable and actionable by resident committees and facility managers.\", \"Co-develop dashboards that combine qualitative resident feedback with quantitative energy trends to refine recommendations.\"]}, {\"title\": \"EduAdmin Cloud: Administrative Management for Small Training Providers\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both are institutional SaaS platforms designed for non-technical users, emphasise simplicity and fast onboarding, provide administrative reporting and compliance features, and target organizations that benefit from recurring subscriptions.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: EduAdmin Cloud focuses on training administration (enrollment, certification); EnergySense focuses on energy analytics and community engagement.\", \"Primary user workflows: EduAdmin supports course and certification management; EnergySense supports meter integration, anonymization and engagement cycles.\", \"Regulatory concerns differ: EduAdmin addresses training compliance; EnergySense addresses data protection with utility data and privacy for residents.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Borrow EduAdmin’s clarity-first onboarding and reporting templates to create simple operational dashboards for property managers and cooperative administrators.\", \"Explore bundling training modules for building staff (administering energy programmes, resident facilitation) within EduAdmin-style workflows.\", \"Share strategies for selling SaaS subscriptions to institutional customers with constrained procurement processes.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SkillSwap Local: Peer-to-Peer Services in Urban Neighborhoods\", \"match\": 55, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasise hyperlocal community networks, trust-first design (verification, reputation), neighbourhood-level engagement, and strengthening local economic/social interactions rather than centralized, surveillance-based models.\", \"differences\": [\"Core function: SkillSwap is a marketplace for time-based local services; EnergySense is an energy-data-driven community engagement platform.\", \"Transaction model: SkillSwap handles payments and transactions between individuals; EnergySense focuses on collective goals, not peer transactions.\", \"Matching: SkillSwap matches people by skills and proximity; EnergySense matches residents to collective energy metrics and building-level insights.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate SkillSwap community channels to recruit local resident champions and volunteers for building energy challenges.\", \"Use SkillSwap’s verification and trust mechanisms to establish resident facilitator reputations for EnergySense programmes.\", \"Co-run neighbourhood pilots that combine skill-exchange events with energy-saving workshops to build local momentum.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Farm2Table Hub: Direct Sourcing Marketplace for Independent Restaurants\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both are B2B/B2G digital marketplaces/services that connect local actors (producers/restaurants or residents/property managers), emphasise regional networks, transparency and operational integration, and aim to produce measurable sustainability benefits.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: Farm2Table is a procurement marketplace for food sourcing; EnergySense is a community energy analytics and engagement platform.\", \"Operational needs: Farm2Table deals with inventory, ordering and logistics; EnergySense handles meter integrations and behaviour-change campaigns.\", \"Customer type: Farm2Table’s primary customers are restaurants and producers; EnergySense’s are housing cooperatives and municipal energy programmes.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Partner with Farm2Table on building-level pilots where communal kitchens or co-op facilities use local sourcing while EnergySense runs energy-awareness interventions to optimise kitchen energy use.\", \"Share regional network-building strategies to bootstrap two-sided markets and increase participation density.\", \"Exchange practices for demonstrating measurable impact to institutional buyers (e.g., environmental reporting templates).\"]}, {\"title\": \"ExpertMatch Pro: On-Demand Access to Independent Specialists\", \"match\": 38, \"similarities\": \"Both are marketplace-like SaaS models that connect institutions to specialised services, emphasise vetting/partnership quality, and target B2B customers with subscription and commission-based monetization options.\", \"differences\": [\"Value proposition: ExpertMatch connects companies to vetted specialists for projects; EnergySense provides ongoing building-level analytics and community engagement services.\", \"Engagement cadence: ExpertMatch supports variable, short-term contracts; EnergySense requires continuous monitoring and long-term resident engagement.\", \"Quality control: ExpertMatch emphasises structured vetting of expertise; EnergySense emphasises anonymization, data security and municipal partnerships.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use ExpertMatch’s curated expert network to provide technical advisory services for EnergySense pilots (data privacy audits, behavioural specialists, municipal procurement advisors).\", \"Offer bundled specialist consulting (policy, measurement verification) via ExpertMatch to municipal clients adopting EnergySense.\", \"Cross-promote services to institutional customers looking for technical or engagement expertise in sustainability programmes.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Voices of the District: Digital Archive of Local Oral Histories\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritise community control, ethical consent management, municipal/cultural partnerships, and public-facing digital platforms that aim to strengthen local identity and civic engagement.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: Voices of the District focuses on cultural heritage and oral histories; EnergySense focuses on energy behaviour and emissions reductions.\", \"Content type: Oral histories and archival media vs time-series energy data and analytics.\", \"Primary outputs: Public archive and educational resources vs energy dashboards and verified consumption reductions.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Collaborate on resident engagement narratives by pairing energy data stories with local oral histories to contextualise living conditions and historical building uses.\", \"Share best practices in participant consent and community governance for ethically managing resident-contributed data and stories.\", \"Co-host community events that combine cultural preservation with energy literacy to deepen resident buy-in.\"]}, {\"title\": \"StageNext: Hybrid Performance Platform for Independent Performing Arts\", \"match\": 22, \"similarities\": \"Both are platform initiatives that support communities (artists/audiences or residents/buildings), provide digital distribution of value, and aim to increase accessibility while generating alternative revenue or impact channels.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector: StageNext serves performing arts and cultural distribution; EnergySense serves residential energy management and municipal climate goals.\", \"Revenue model: StageNext uses revenue-sharing on ticketing and subscriptions; EnergySense uses subscriptions and service contracts with institutions.\", \"Core functionality: StageNext supports streaming, ticketing and rights management; EnergySense integrates meter data, anonymization and community challenges.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Partner to run hybrid cultural events in apartment common areas or online to surface energy-awareness themes and engage residents.\", \"Share audience engagement and ticketing/registration mechanics to encourage attendance and participation in building challenges or trainings.\", \"Explore bundling cultural programming with energy campaigns to reach diverse resident groups.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Memory Trails: Cultural Routes for Territorial Memory and Education\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both engage local communities and municipalities, combine physical place-based interventions with a digital layer, and emphasise ethical co-creation and educational value for residents and visitors.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain: Memory Trails focuses on heritage routes and place-based education; EnergySense focuses on building energy data and collective efficiency actions.\", \"User experience: Memory Trails is experiential and location-based storytelling; EnergySense is data-driven dashboards and community challenges.\", \"Primary metrics: Memory Trails measures educational and cultural engagement; EnergySense measures energy savings and emissions reductions.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Create joint place-based campaigns where Memory Trails’ location narratives include historical context about buildings and energy use, linking heritage to sustainable living practices.\", \"Leverage Memory Trails’ school and educational partnerships to embed energy literacy modules for students living in multi-family buildings.\", \"Share community co-creation methods to ensure resident voices shape both cultural and energy interventions.\"]}, {\"title\": \"OpenCouncil: Transparent Decision Tracking for Local Governments\", \"match\": 58, \"similarities\": \"Both are B2G/B2B SaaS solutions aimed at municipalities, focus on clear, accessible dashboards and traceability, support institutional workflows, and aim to strengthen public trust through transparency and measurable outcomes.\", \"differences\": [\"Primary purpose: OpenCouncil focuses on decision lifecycle transparency for governance; EnergySense focuses on energy analytics and community behaviour change.\", \"Users: OpenCouncil is primarily for municipal staff and citizens; EnergySense targets housing cooperatives, property managers and residents.\", \"Integration points: OpenCouncil integrates agendas and votes; EnergySense integrates smart-meter data and anonymized building metrics.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate EnergySense building-level energy outcomes into OpenCouncil’s public-facing interfaces so municipalities can link policy decisions to verified energy impacts.\", \"Co-design procurement and reporting templates that help municipalities commission and monitor EnergySense pilots through the OpenCouncil platform.\", \"Share UX practices for presenting technical information in plain language tailored to non-expert public audiences.\"]}, {\"title\": \"CivicPulse: Inclusive Digital Consultations for Public Policy Design\", \"match\": 62, \"similarities\": \"Both target public institutions (municipalities), emphasise inclusive, ethically governed digital participation, use human-moderated synthesis rather than opaque automation, and aim to convert engagement into actionable institutional change with traceable outcomes.\", \"differences\": [\"Core function: CivicPulse runs structured civic consultations; EnergySense delivers aggregated energy analytics and collective behavioural programmes.\", \"Participant model: CivicPulse is designed for broad public consultation workflows (multilingual, offline channels); EnergySense focuses on building resident communities and behaviour change within defined housing units.\", \"Primary outputs: CivicPulse produces consultation insights and policy inputs; EnergySense produces verified energy reduction metrics and building dashboards.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Co-run municipal pilots combining energy-focused consultations with CivicPulse’s structured methods to co-design building-level interventions and increase resident inclusion.\", \"Share synthesis and human-moderation workflows to translate resident feedback into targeted energy recommendations and policy proposals.\", \"Integrate CivicPulse’s offline inclusion channels with EnergySense onboarding to reach residents with limited digital access.\"]}, {\"title\": \"TrustVote Lab: Secure Pilots for Digital Voting Research\", \"match\": 33, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritise careful, research-driven pilots, ethical governance and transparency, and avoid risky deployments without evidence; each values independent evaluation and public reporting of results and limitations.\", \"differences\": [\"Purpose: TrustVote Lab is a research framework for digital voting pilots; EnergySense is an operational platform for reducing building energy consumption.\", \"Stakeholders: TrustVote’s stakeholders are academic and electoral research bodies; EnergySense’s stakeholders are housing cooperatives, utilities and municipalities.\", \"Output type: TrustVote outputs audit reports and research findings; EnergySense outputs dashboards, engagement campaigns and verified energy savings.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Adopt TrustVote Lab’s independent-audit and transparent reporting methodology to validate EnergySense’s measurement and verification protocols for energy savings.\", \"Co-design non-binding experimental pilots to test alternative resident engagement mechanisms under controlled conditions and publish findings.\", \"Leverage TrustVote’s multidisciplinary governance approaches to ensure EnergySense pilots meet ethical and legal scrutiny, especially where data-sharing agreements with utilities are involved.\"]}, {\"title\": \"NeighbourLab: Participatory Solutions for Urban Social Challenges\", \"match\": 72, \"similarities\": \"High alignment on community-led, participatory design; emphasis on local ownership, municipal partnerships, participatory governance and long-term social impact; both use digital platforms to enable resident co-creation and institutional collaboration to solve neighbourhood-level problems.\", \"differences\": [\"Primary emphasis: NeighbourLab explicitly emphasises participatory budgeting and co-decision with resource allocation; EnergySense focuses on collective energy efficiency and technical integration with smart meters.\", \"Decision scope: NeighbourLab often involves funding allocation and deliberation; EnergySense focuses on changing daily energy behaviours and measuring consumption outcomes.\", \"Monetization: NeighbourLab positions as B2G/B2B with facilitation services; EnergySense is SaaS subscription/service contracts tied to buildings and municipalities.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Build integrated pilots where NeighbourLab’s participatory processes define local energy priorities and allocate small budgets to resident-driven energy initiatives supported by EnergySense measurement tools.\", \"Combine NeighbourLab’s deliberative resources with EnergySense dashboards to let communities decide which energy interventions to trial and fund.\", \"Share facilitation and long-term engagement toolkits so resident committees maintain momentum after pilot phases.\"]}]');
INSERT INTO `projects` (`id`, `email`, `created_at`, `category_id`, `title`, `description`, `authors`, `link`, `pitch`, `canvas`, `summary`, `script`, `detail`, `score`, `evaluation`, `conversation`, `likes`, `relationships_local`, `relationships_global`) VALUES
(25, 'lisa@gmail.com', '2026-01-30 18:23:47', 'sustainability', 'SoilBack: Regenerative Practices for Small-Scale Agriculture', 'SoilBack is a farmer-centered service platform delivering region-adapted agronomic guidance, peer-learning and practical indicator-based monitoring to help small-scale farmers adopt regenerative pract', 'Lisa', '', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K5NgaIyiAEY', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/SUSTAINABILITY/Sustainability_SoilBack_Canvas.pdf', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com/rankingprojects/docs/SUSTAINABILITY/Sustainability_SoilBack_Executive_Summary.pdf', 'Recommended length: ~80 seconds\nTone: Practical, trustworthy, field-focused\n1. Opening & Personal Introduction (5–8s)\nHello, my name is Alex, and I’m part of the team behind SoilBack.\n2. Project Definition (10–12s)\nSoilBack is a service platform that helps small-scale farmers transition toward regenerative\npractices that improve soil health and long-term resilience.\n3. Problem Statement (15–18s)\nMany small farms are dealing with declining soil health, rising input costs, and increasing climate\npressure.\nAt the same time, many sustainability solutions rely on generic advice or carbon offset models that\ndon’t reflect what actually happens on the field.\n4. Solution Explanation (15–18s)\nSoilBack provides region-adapted guidance on practices like crop rotation, reduced tillage, and soil\ncover.\nFarmers receive practical recommendations, learn from peers, and track gradual improvements\nusing transparent indicators such as soil organic matter and input reduction.\n5. Key Innovation / Differentiator (15–18s)\nThe key innovation of SoilBack is its focus on real practices, not abstract claims.\nThe platform does not sell carbon credits or offsets. Instead, it supports measurable, on-the-ground\nimprovements that fit farmers’ economic realities.\n6. Target Audience (10–12s)\nSoilBack is designed for small-scale farmers, cooperatives, and agri-food partners committed to\nbuilding more resilient supply chains.\n7. Vision / Impact Statement (5–8s)\nSoilBack is not about quick fixes—it’s about restoring soil, knowledge, and resilience for the long\nterm.\n8. Closing (3–5s)\nThank you.', 'SoilBack is a service platform supporting small-scale farmers in transitioning toward regenerative agricultural practices. The project addresses soil degradation, biodiversity loss, and long-term farm resilience by combining practical guidance, peer learning, and impact monitoring.<p>\nFarmers receive tailored recommendations on crop rotation, reduced tillage, and soil cover strategies adapted to their region. Rather than making generalized claims, SoilBack focuses on gradual improvement and transparent indicators such as soil organic matter, input reduction, and water retention proxies.<p>\nThe business model blends subscriptions with partnerships involving cooperatives and agri-food buyers interested in more sustainable supply chains. SoilBack does not sell carbon credits or offsets; instead, it emphasizes measurable, on-the-ground practices. The project’s objective is to improve environmental outcomes while maintaining farmers’ economic viability.', 69, '{\"score\": 69, \"evaluation\": \"Per-criterion scores (0–4):\\n1) Identified Environmental Problem & Urgency: 4 — Clear problem (soil degradation, biodiversity loss, input costs) well contextualized for small-scale farms and justified urgency.\\n2) Sustainability & Circular Economy Approach: 3 — Coherent regenerative approach focused on soil health and reduced inputs; limited explicit circular-economy design details (nutrient/waste flows).\\n3) Real & Measurable Environmental Impact: 3 — Practical indicators (soil organic matter, input use, water-retention proxies) selected, but no measurement protocol, baselines, or quantitative targets provided.\\n4) Alignment Between Environmental Impact & Business Model: 4 — Business model (advisory/subscription, no offsets) is well aligned with delivering practice-based environmental outcomes.\\n5) Technical & Operational Feasibility: 3 — Conceptually feasible with identified resources (agronomists, platform); early-stage (pre-MVP) and requires capacity-building for regional adaptation.\\n6) Regulatory Compliance & ESG Framework: 0 — No evident discussion of environmental regulations, certifications, or ESG/legal risk mitigation in the materials.\\n7) Environmental Scalability & Replicability: 3 — Scalability via cooperatives and networks is plausible; regional adaptation and advisory capacity are clear limiting factors.\\n8) Team & Green Execution Capacity: 2 — Roles and skills needed are identified but the team’s demonstrated experience and track record are not documented.\\nSummary: Total 22/32 ? final score 69/100. SoilBack presents a credible, well-aligned practice-first model with good potential, but needs stronger measurement systems, regulatory/ESG coverage, and demonstrated execution capacity before scaling.\", \"strengths\": [\"Clear identification of a genuine and relevant environmental problem for small-scale farmers (soil degradation, input dependency, climate vulnerability).\", \"Practice-first approach that explicitly avoids carbon-offset commodification and focuses on on-farm regenerative actions.\", \"Transparent selection of practical indicators (soil organic matter, input use, water-retention proxies) for tracking progress.\", \"Business model aligned with impact (subscription/advisory, cooperative partnerships) rather than monetizing offsets.\", \"Explicit emphasis on regional adaptation and peer learning, which supports farmer adoption and contextual relevance.\", \"Scalability strategy leveraging cooperatives and networks is realistic for reaching fragmented smallholder populations.\"], \"weaknesses\": [\"No defined measurement methodology, baseline data, or quantitative targets for environmental outcomes—limits verifiability of impact.\", \"Regulatory, certification, and broader ESG considerations are not addressed, posing legal and market risks (e.g., claims, procurement requirements).\", \"Project is early-stage (pre-MVP) with limited evidence of operational pilots or field-proven results.\", \"Team composition and demonstrable experience in delivering regenerative/advisory services are not documented.\", \"Circular-economy specifics (e.g., nutrient recycling, waste valorization, life-cycle perspective) are underdeveloped.\", \"Dependency on advisory capacity and regional adaptation may constrain rapid scale without clear plans to decentralize or train partners.\"], \"recommendations\": [\"Develop and publish a measurement framework: define indicators, standardized sampling/measurement protocols, baseline assessment methods, frequency, and data quality controls.\", \"Set clear, time-bound quantitative targets (e.g., % increase in soil organic matter, % reduction in synthetic input use, proxy water-holding improvements) for pilot cohorts and report results publicly.\", \"Design and run explicit field pilots (diverse regions) to validate recommendations, collect empirical impact data, and iterate on the advisory model before broader scaling.\", \"Document team credentials and recruit experienced agronomists, soil scientists, and implementation leads; form partnerships with research institutions for monitoring and credibility.\", \"Address regulatory and procurement requirements: map relevant local regulations, certification expectations of buyers, and an ESG risk register; define policies to avoid misleading environmental claims.\", \"Strengthen circular-economy elements in guidance (e.g., on-farm nutrient cycling, organic amendments, residue management) to deepen systemic sustainability benefits.\", \"Develop a capacity-scaling plan: train farmer trainers, leverage cooperatives for decentralized advisory delivery, and build digital tools that reduce per-farm advisory cost.\", \"Implement transparent reporting and governance (data access, consent, verification) to build trust with farmers and buyers and reduce greenwashing risk.\"]}', '', '', '[{\"title\": \"ReLoop Materials: Circular Packaging for Local Food Producers\", \"match\": 60, \"similarities\": \"Both are service-oriented sustainability platforms targeting small-scale actors in local food systems, emphasize prevention-first approaches (reuse/practice-first rather than offsets), rely on cooperatives and networks for distribution, use subscription or recurring revenue models, and offer measurable environmental impact reporting tied to operational workflows.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain focus: SoilBack targets on-farm soil health and regenerative agronomy; ReLoop focuses on packaging waste reduction and logistics.\", \"Core offerings: SoilBack delivers agronomic guidance, peer learning and soil indicators; ReLoop provides physical reusable containers, cleaning logistics, and reuse-tracking.\", \"Key resources and operations: SoilBack depends on agronomists, field coordinators and soil monitoring; ReLoop requires container procurement, cleaning facilities and transport logistics.\", \"Impact metrics: SoilBack measures soil organic matter, input reduction and resilience; ReLoop measures reuse cycles and packaging waste avoided.\", \"Capital profile: SoilBack has moderate fixed costs tied to advisory capacity; ReLoop has higher upfront capital expenditure for containers and logistics infrastructure.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Pilot joint supply-chain programs where SoilBack works with farmers supplying producers using ReLoop containers to demonstrate combined farm-level regenerative outcomes and packaging circularity.\", \"Shared cooperative partnerships to offer bundled subscriptions (agronomic support + circular packaging) to producer networks, increasing value proposition and retention.\", \"Data-sharing pilot to correlate improved farm practices (e.g., reduced residues, changed packaging needs) with packaging reuse logistics and sustainability reporting for buyers.\", \"Cross-training exchange: ReLoop operations teams advise on logistics and lifecycle tracking; SoilBack shares farmer community engagement methods to improve producer onboarding.\"]}, {\"title\": \"EnergySense Communities: Collective Energy Efficiency for Apartment Buildings\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both are platform-driven, data-informed services that use community engagement and collective action (peer learning / building-level challenges) to achieve measurable environmental outcomes; both target institutional partners (cooperatives, property managers or agricultural cooperatives) and favor subscription/B2B revenue models with scalable software components and an emphasis on trust and non-intrusive engagement.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector and beneficiaries: SoilBack serves small-scale farmers and agri-food supply chains; EnergySense targets apartment residents, housing cooperatives and building managers.\", \"Core data and integrations: SoilBack focuses on farm practice and soil indicators; EnergySense integrates smart meter energy data with anonymization and building dashboards.\", \"Primary behavior change mechanism: SoilBack emphasizes agronomic practice adoption and peer farmer learning; EnergySense emphasizes collective energy challenges and anonymized building-level feedback.\", \"Operational needs: SoilBack requires agronomy expertise, field coordination and regional adaptation; EnergySense requires data engineering, smart meter integrations and privacy/security systems.\", \"Scalability dynamics: SoilBack depends on regional agronomic adaptation and advisory capacity; EnergySense has lower marginal costs per additional building once data integrations are in place.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share community engagement and behavior-change design patterns (collective challenges, peer circles) to improve farmer adoption pathways and resident participation design.\", \"Joint development of modular monitoring/dashboard components that can be adapted for both soil and energy indicators to reduce development costs and speed MVPs.\", \"Pilot integrated rural community programs addressing both farm-level regeneration (SoilBack) and energy efficiency in farm housing or shared facilities (EnergySense) to demonstrate holistic resilience benefits.\", \"Exchange on privacy-first and trust-building practices to ensure farmer data sovereignty and resident data anonymization standards are robust and culturally appropriate.\"]}]', '[{\"title\": \"MindAnchor: Evidence-Based Mental Health Support for Young Adults\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both are digital service platforms that deliver behavior-change support via structured, evidence-informed programs, emphasize ethical boundaries and human-in-the-loop support, use subscription-style monetization and aim for scalable, low-cost delivery to specific user groups.\", \"differences\": [\"Sector and outcomes differ: mental wellbeing vs soil health and farm resilience.\", \"Professional validation: licensed psychologists (MindAnchor) vs agronomists and soil scientists (SoilBack).\", \"Regulatory and clinical constraints for mental health are stricter than for agronomic advisory.\", \"Interaction models differ: short daily modules and reflective exercises vs farm practice tracking and field demonstrations.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange design patterns for sustaining behavior change (micro-modules, habit reinforcement) adapted to farmer practice adoption.\", \"Share privacy-first, consent and data protection practices for user-sensitive data.\", \"Pilot joint UX experiments on motivation, onboarding and retention techniques (e.g., habit nudges for practice adoption).\"]}, {\"title\": \"CareLink Home: Coordinated Support for Elderly People Living Alone\", \"match\": 35, \"similarities\": \"Both are service platforms focused on vulnerable, place?based populations and emphasize human-in-the-loop responses, dignity/consent, longitudinal monitoring and partnerships with intermediaries (cooperatives/municipalities).\", \"differences\": [\"Target users and problems differ: elderly independent living and emergency detection vs soil degradation and farm resilience.\", \"CareLink uses sensor and pattern-detection for safety alerts; SoilBack monitors agronomic indicators and practice adoption.\", \"Revenue model orientation: B2G institutional contracts (CareLink) vs mixed farmer subscriptions and cooperative partnerships (SoilBack).\", \"Intervention types: care coordination and emergency response vs agronomic advice and peer learning.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share human-centered, consent-first design approaches and pattern-detection governance.\", \"Adapt CareLink’s human-follow-up and alert triage workflows to farmer-support escalation (e.g., local field coordinators responding to critical soil/farm indicators).\", \"Joint workshops on multi-stakeholder onboarding and institutional contracting for public or cooperative partners.\"]}, {\"title\": \"MoveWell Rehab: Personalized Physical Rehabilitation for Chronic Conditions\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both provide personalized, professional-guided programs to improve long-term outcomes (adherence to rehabilitation vs adoption of regenerative practices), combine digital delivery with professional oversight, and focus on measurable progress tracking over time.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain and outcome metrics differ: clinical mobility and pain reduction vs soil organic matter, input reductions and resilience.\", \"MoveWell uses guided video exercises and remote professional adjustments; SoilBack relies on field observations, agronomic recommendations and peer learning.\", \"Regulatory and clinical safety constraints for physiotherapy are more prescriptive than for agronomy advisory.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Exchange methods to maximize adherence to multi-step programs (reminders, progress visualization, professional check-ins).\", \"Pilot remote coaching models where agronomists use structured progress reviews similar to physiotherapist adjustments.\", \"Co-develop UX patterns for low-digital-literacy users and accessible instructional content for practice execution.\"]}, {\"title\": \"PathLearn: Personalized Learning Pathways for Secondary Education\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both center on tailored, scaffolded learning/adoption pathways, keep a practitioner (teacher/farmer) in the loop, emphasize formative assessment and progress tracking, and plan B2B institutional pilots (schools/cooperatives).\", \"differences\": [\"Content domain differs: curriculum-aligned student learning vs region-adapted agronomic practices.\", \"Educational models emphasize mastery learning and classroom workflows; SoilBack works with farm cycles, field trials and on-farm constraints.\", \"Buyer types: school districts and education authorities vs farmer cooperatives and agri-food buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Apply mastery-learning and formative-assessment frameworks to structure farmer learning pathways and competency milestones.\", \"Reuse teacher-in-the-loop design patterns for agronomist oversight and farmer decision dashboards.\", \"Co-design training modules for extension agents using PathLearn’s adaptivity and teacher support approaches.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SkillBridge: Practice-Based Digital Training for Workforce Reskilling\", \"match\": 55, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritize practice-first learning, competency demonstration, collaboration/peer feedback and co-design with domain experts. Each is a platformed service aiming to produce real, verifiable changes in participant capability and employability/resilience.\", \"differences\": [\"SkillBridge targets adult workforce reskilling and formal competency assessment; SoilBack focuses on on?farm practice adoption and soil outcomes rather than certified competencies.\", \"Assessment models differ: SkillBridge emphasizes rubrics and demonstrable projects; SoilBack emphasizes gradual field indicators and practice tracking.\", \"Customer segments differ: employers and training centers vs small-scale farmers and cooperatives.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Adapt competency-based assessment methods to define farmer competencies for regenerative practices and track demonstrated skills on-farm.\", \"Co-develop practice-based training modules and peer-led cohort pilots for farmer groups.\", \"Share mentorship and evaluator networks to scale quality assurance of practical learning.\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReadTogether: Inclusive Literacy Support for Early Learners\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasize pedagogy-first design, low-complexity, inclusion and family/community engagement rather than heavy algorithmic assessment, and prioritize trust and accessibility in low-resource contexts.\", \"differences\": [\"Target learners and learning goals differ (children learning to read vs farmers adopting regenerative practices).\", \"ReadTogether’s core features are phonics, audio support and family engagement; SoilBack centers on agronomy, field demonstrations and cooperative onboarding.\", \"Revenue and institutional buyers: schools and education grants vs cooperative agreements and farmer subscriptions.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share approaches to family/community engagement and low-friction, offline-support techniques for low-tech contexts.\", \"Borrow lightweight progress indicators and simple usability patterns to reduce digital complexity for farmers.\", \"Test integrated community-based learning sessions that combine literacy-style guided practice with farmer peer-learning formats.\"]}, {\"title\": \"LocalHands: Community-Based Support for Informal Caregivers\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both are community-oriented platforms that strengthen peer networks, reduce isolation, rely on local facilitation, and partner with municipalities and NGOs. Each emphasizes dignity, bottom-up participation and non?paternalistic support.\", \"differences\": [\"LocalHands focuses on informal caregiving and social support; SoilBack focuses on agronomic practice adoption and farm resilience.\", \"Operational models: community facilitation and mutual aid vs technical agronomy advisory and monitoring.\", \"Revenue models lean more to public funding and grants for LocalHands, compared with subscription and cooperative partnerships for SoilBack.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share community facilitation techniques, local facilitator training and retention strategies applicable to farmer learning circles.\", \"Exchange impact measurement approaches for social outcomes and wellbeing (caregiver support vs farmer livelihood resilience).\", \"Pilot cross-sector community programs that combine social support and farm practice exchange (addressing rural isolation among smallholders).\"]}, {\"title\": \"AccessPath: Inclusive Employment Pathways for People with Disabilities\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritize person-/user-centered co-design, guided onboarding, partnership networks and long-term support to improve livelihood outcomes. They emphasize embedding beneficiaries in decision-making and tailoring solutions to individual constraints.\", \"differences\": [\"AccessPath targets inclusive employment and workplace accommodations; SoilBack targets agronomic practices and on-farm resilience.\", \"Core outputs differ: job retention and workplace inclusion vs soil health metrics and reduced input dependency.\", \"AccessPath’s business model is B2B/B2G employer contracts; SoilBack targets farmers and cooperatives with subscription/partnership revenue.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Apply co-design methods from AccessPath to involve farmers in shaping advisory tools and service offers.\", \"Share approaches for individualized support plans and long-term retention metrics that could inform farmer advisory journeys.\", \"Pilot inclusive workforce pathways on farms (e.g., roles for people with disabilities within regenerative supply chains).\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReLoop Materials: Circular Packaging for Local Food Producers\", \"match\": 75, \"similarities\": \"High alignment on target customers (small-scale/local food producers), system-oriented sustainability goals, partnerships with cooperatives/distributors, B2B recurring revenue models, and emphasis on prevention-focused environmental impact rather than offsets.\", \"differences\": [\"Core offering differs: ReLoop provides reusable packaging logistics and cleaning vs SoilBack provides agronomic guidance and soil monitoring.\", \"Operational needs differ: heavy logistics, cleaning infrastructure and container capital (ReLoop) vs agronomic expertise and field extension capacity (SoilBack).\", \"Impact metrics differ though complementary: number of reuse cycles and waste avoided (ReLoop) vs soil organic matter and input reduction (SoilBack).\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Pilot integrated services with producer cooperatives where SoilBack supports regenerative practice adoption and ReLoop supplies circular packaging—creating joint sustainability reporting.\", \"Combine data streams to offer buyers coherent sustainability stories (regenerative practices + reduced packaging waste).\", \"Coordinate cooperative-level partnerships to bundle advisory, logistics and market access services for small producers.\"]}, {\"title\": \"EnergySense Communities: Collective Energy Efficiency for Apartment Buildings\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both use aggregated, privacy-preserving monitoring and dashboards to drive collective behavior change, emphasize community engagement and low-infrastructure interventions, and target cooperative or multi-stakeholder adoption models.\", \"differences\": [\"EnergySense targets urban multi-family buildings and energy consumption; SoilBack targets farms and soil/ecosystem outcomes.\", \"Data sources differ (smart meters vs on-farm indicators and practice reports) and intervention rhythms (daily/seasonal energy vs seasonal farm cycles).\", \"Customer types differ: housing cooperatives and municipalities vs farmer cooperatives and agri-food buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share privacy-preserving aggregation and community-challenge mechanics to encourage collective practice adoption among farmer groups.\", \"Exchange methods for resident/responder engagement and long-term reporting that maintain trust across households/farms.\", \"Co-develop dashboards illustrating collective resource outcomes (e.g., water retention benefits at landscape scale).\"]}, {\"title\": \"FlowOps: Workflow Automation for Small Professional Services Firms\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS platforms serving small-scale operators with a focus on simplifying workflows, embedding best-practice templates, low onboarding friction and recurring subscription revenue, and aim to reduce operational overhead so users can focus on core work.\", \"differences\": [\"FlowOps targets small professional services firms and automates administrative workflows; SoilBack delivers agronomic advice, field coordination and impact monitoring.\", \"Core features differ: no-code workflow templates and integrations (FlowOps) vs agronomy content, field demonstration and farmer peer learning (SoilBack).\", \"Value metrics differ: administrative time saved vs environmental and agronomic performance.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use FlowOps-style templates to operationalize SoilBack’s advisory workflows (farmer onboarding, trial scheduling, cooperative reporting).\", \"Integrate lightweight workflow automation for field coordinators to reduce administrative load.\", \"Share approaches to template libraries and guided setup for non-technical users.\"]}, {\"title\": \"InsightPulse: Customer Feedback Analytics for Product Teams\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both are data-driven platforms that centralize qualitative inputs, emphasize human-in-the-loop synthesis and traceability from inputs to decisions, and aim to turn scattered signals into accountable actions.\", \"differences\": [\"InsightPulse focuses on product team feedback (NLP, text analytics) while SoilBack focuses on agronomic practice data, on-farm indicators and peer learning narratives.\", \"Technology emphasis differs: heavy NLP and text clustering (InsightPulse) vs indicator monitoring, visualization and agronomic rule-sets (SoilBack).\", \"Primary buyers differ: product teams and tech companies vs farmers/cooperatives and agri-food buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Adopt InsightPulse’s feedback-to-decision traceability model to link farmer feedback and field observations to advisory updates and roadmap decisions.\", \"Pilot thematic synthesis of farmer reports (free-text field notes) using lightweight NLP to surface common barriers to adoption.\", \"Share dashboards that document how farmer inputs led to updated recommendations, increasing trust and transparency.\"]}, {\"title\": \"EduAdmin Cloud: Administrative Management for Small Training Providers\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both support small providers (training organizations or farmer-support programs) with clear, low-complexity SaaS tools, prioritize non-technical UX, and enable institutional or program-level management and reporting.\", \"differences\": [\"EduAdmin is focused on course and certification administration for training providers; SoilBack delivers agronomic guidance, field support and impact monitoring for farms.\", \"Core modules differ: scheduling/enrollment/certification vs practice tracking, field trial management and soil indicator reporting.\", \"Primary customers: training providers and vocational centers vs farmers and cooperatives.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use EduAdmin’s admin modules to manage SoilBack training cohorts, scheduling, certifications of farmer competencies and reporting.\", \"Co-develop onboarding and compliance workflows for large cooperative-based training programs.\", \"Borrow simplicity-first UX patterns for non-technical administrators and field coordinators.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SkillSwap Local: Peer-to-Peer Services in Urban Neighborhoods\", \"match\": 55, \"similarities\": \"Both platforms are grounded in local networks, trust-first design and enabling peer exchange (services or farmer knowledge), focus on hyperlocal matching and rely on verification, reputation and community incentives to build sustainable supply.\", \"differences\": [\"SkillSwap is a marketplace for time-based local services in urban neighborhoods; SoilBack is an advisory and monitoring service for agricultural practice uptake.\", \"Transaction model differs: individual service bookings and payments vs subscription/advisory relationships and cooperative agreements.\", \"Operational geography tends to be dense urban vs rural/regions with small farms.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Pilot local service exchange models for farm labor, equipment-sharing or seasonal help using SkillSwap’s hyperlocal marketplace design.\", \"Adapt trust and verification systems (identity, reputation) to support peer-to-peer farmer exchanges within SoilBack communities.\", \"Test neighborhood-style onboarding and local incentives to increase reciprocity and peer learning among farmers.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Farm2Table Hub: Direct Sourcing Marketplace for Independent Restaurants\", \"match\": 80, \"similarities\": \"Strong alignment: both serve small and mid-sized agricultural producers, work with cooperatives and buyer partnerships, target local/regional food system resilience, and aim to align value and impact with operational practices rather than offset claims.\", \"differences\": [\"Farm2Table is a B2B marketplace matching producers to restaurants and handling ordering/transactions; SoilBack provides agronomic advisory, monitoring and capacity building.\", \"Core capabilities differ: logistics/order management and marketplace operations (Farm2Table) vs agronomy expertise and on-farm advisory (SoilBack).\", \"Revenue focus: transaction commissions (Farm2Table) vs subscriptions and partnership fees (SoilBack).\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate SoilBack advisory signals with Farm2Table marketplace to offer buyers visibility on regenerative practice adoption and premium sourcing.\", \"Coordinate pilots where Farm2Table aggregates demand for producers participating in SoilBack, creating market incentives for regenerative transitions.\", \"Share cooperative onboarding and regional network strategies to increase producer participation and data flows between advisory and procurement.\"]}, {\"title\": \"ExpertMatch Pro: On-Demand Access to Independent Specialists\", \"match\": 60, \"similarities\": \"Both connect users to vetted domain experts (agronomists in SoilBack’s case) with a quality-first, human-mediated approach, enable short-term, high-value engagements and emphasize trust, vetting and curated matching.\", \"differences\": [\"ExpertMatch is a horizontal expert marketplace across many domains and B2B-focused; SoilBack is a domain-specific advisory service for small-scale agriculture with embedded peer learning and field support.\", \"Business models vary in focus (commissioned expert contracts vs recurring advisory/subscription services).\", \"Scale and user journeys differ: ad-hoc specialist engagements vs ongoing farmer advisory relationships.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use ExpertMatch’s vetting and matching methodology to create a curated pool of regional agronomists and technical specialists accessible through SoilBack.\", \"Pilot on-demand specialist sessions for complex agronomic problems within SoilBack’s platform.\", \"Exchange quality assurance and performance-tracking practices for expert engagements.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Voices of the District: Digital Archive of Local Oral Histories\", \"match\": 25, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasize community control, ethical consent, participatory content creation and long-term public value through documenting lived experience and local knowledge.\", \"differences\": [\"Voices of the District is a cultural archive of oral histories; SoilBack is an applied agronomic advisory and monitoring service.\", \"Primary outputs differ: preserved testimonies and educational archives vs measurable soil and farm performance improvements.\", \"Funding and sustainability models differ (grants/public funding for archives vs subscription/partnership revenue for SoilBack).\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Collaborate to document and archive traditional farming knowledge and local regenerative techniques as oral histories.\", \"Design consented storytelling features within SoilBack to surface farmer experiences and spread peer-learning content ethically.\", \"Use community-archiving practices to build trust and preserve contextual knowledge about local agronomic methods.\"]}, {\"title\": \"StageNext: Hybrid Performance Platform for Independent Performing Arts\", \"match\": 20, \"similarities\": \"Both are platforms that support creator-controlled content distribution, fair revenue-sharing and hybrid (local + digital) access models, and stress respecting practitioner autonomy and integrity.\", \"differences\": [\"StageNext targets performing arts and audience distribution; SoilBack targets farming practice adoption and cooperative support.\", \"Core technology needs (high-quality streaming) differ from field-data collection and agronomy dashboards.\", \"Audience/market dynamics: arts audiences and ticketing vs farmer/cooperative subscriptions and buyer relationships.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Borrow StageNext’s revenue-sharing and creator-control mechanisms to design fair benefit-sharing models for farmer-generated content and demonstrations.\", \"Pilot community events where farmers present demonstrations or seasonal showcases using hybrid (in-person + streamed) formats.\", \"Share audience-engagement practices to improve farmer-to-buyer storytelling around regenerative practices.\"]}, {\"title\": \"Memory Trails: Cultural Routes for Territorial Memory and Education\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both value territory-specific knowledge, community co-creation, educational outcomes and integrating physical practices with digital narratives. Each stresses ethical contextualization and community validation.\", \"differences\": [\"Memory Trails focuses on cultural heritage, walking routes and place-based storytelling; SoilBack is focused on soil health, agronomic interventions and farm resilience.\", \"Output modalities differ: physical signage and curated routes vs practice guidance, monitoring and peer exchanges.\", \"Primary audiences differ: tourists/educators/residents vs farmers, cooperatives and buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Co-create agro-cultural trails that showcase traditional regenerative practices, linking SoilBack field sites with Memory Trails educational narratives.\", \"Use Memory Trails’ place-based storytelling techniques to contextualize local agricultural knowledge and increase public appreciation of regenerative farming.\", \"Develop educational materials for schools that combine territorial memory with hands-on farming demonstrations.\"]}, {\"title\": \"OpenCouncil: Transparent Decision Tracking for Local Governments\", \"match\": 35, \"similarities\": \"Both provide structured, transparent dashboards and reporting aimed at improving institutional accountability and trust, integrate with existing administrative workflows, and target partnerships with public bodies and cooperatives.\", \"differences\": [\"OpenCouncil is focused on municipal decision traceability and public governance; SoilBack focuses on farm-level practice adoption and environmental outcomes.\", \"Data types and governance differ: legislative agendas and voting records vs farm practice logs and soil indicators.\", \"Primary end users differ: citizens and municipal staff vs farmers, cooperatives and agri-food buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate SoilBack impact reporting with municipal agricultural programs and decision tracking to increase policy transparency and program accountability.\", \"Adopt OpenCouncil’s plain-language contextualization approach to explain SoilBack indicators and farm program decisions to broader stakeholder groups.\", \"Pilot co-designed reporting for public funding programs supporting regenerative agriculture.\"]}, {\"title\": \"CivicPulse: Inclusive Digital Consultations for Public Policy Design\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both emphasize structured, inclusive participation, human moderation, ethical governance of digital consultations and B2G partnerships to co-design policies or practices with stakeholder groups (citizens or farmers).\", \"differences\": [\"CivicPulse targets public-policy consultations and inclusion; SoilBack is an advisory service working directly with farmers to change on-farm practice.\", \"Functional focus differs: moderated deliberation and synthesis vs agronomic guidance, field monitoring and peer exchange.\", \"CivicPulse includes offline participation workflows via community partners geared to civic inputs; SoilBack emphasizes field demonstration and farmer networks.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use CivicPulse’s structured consultation tools to run farmer co-design sessions for regional practice recommendations and program design.\", \"Adopt CivicPulse’s multilingual and accessibility-first approaches to include marginalized farmers and non-digital participation channels.\", \"Co-develop synthesis workflows to translate farmer consultation outputs into actionable agronomic recommendations and program policies.\"]}, {\"title\": \"TrustVote Lab: Secure Pilots for Digital Voting Research\", \"match\": 25, \"similarities\": \"Both prioritize research-first pilots, evidence-based evaluation, transparency about limitations and cautious, non?speculative claims—avoiding premature commercialization or overclaiming impacts.\", \"differences\": [\"TrustVote Lab focuses on safe, non-binding pilots for digital voting and cryptographic auditability; SoilBack focuses on regenerative farming practices and farmer advisory.\", \"Target stakeholders and technical domains are distinct (electoral systems and security researchers vs agronomy and extension services).\", \"Funding and outputs skew research/grant-based for TrustVote Lab vs subscription and partnership revenue for SoilBack.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Share rigorous pilot design, independent-audit and transparent reporting methods to strengthen SoilBack’s evidence and evaluation practices.\", \"Adapt TrustVote Lab’s multidisciplinary governance and public reporting norms for transparent field trial documentation in agriculture.\", \"Co-author methodological guidance on safe, non-binding piloting and public disclosure of limitations.\"]}, {\"title\": \"NeighbourLab: Participatory Solutions for Urban Social Challenges\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both foreground participatory co-creation, community facilitation, long-term local ownership and institution-as-facilitator models; each aims to move from consultation to co-creation with measurable local outcomes.\", \"differences\": [\"NeighbourLab targets urban social challenges and participatory budgeting; SoilBack addresses agronomic practice adoption in rural and small-scale farm contexts.\", \"Operational facilitation differs by context: neighborhood assemblies and urban budgets vs farmer learning circles and cooperative program design.\", \"Revenue models and institutional buyers may differ (municipal contracts for NeighbourLab; cooperatives and buyers for SoilBack).\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Apply NeighbourLab’s deliberation and participatory budgeting tools to cooperative-led prioritization of regenerative interventions and local resource allocation.\", \"Share facilitator training, moderation toolkits and participation diversity measurement practices adapted to farming communities.\", \"Pilot participatory pilots where farmer communities co-design regionally tailored SoilBack offerings and incentives.\"]}]');
INSERT INTO `projects` (`id`, `email`, `created_at`, `category_id`, `title`, `description`, `authors`, `link`, `pitch`, `canvas`, `summary`, `script`, `detail`, `score`, `evaluation`, `conversation`, `likes`, `relationships_local`, `relationships_global`) VALUES
(26, 'esteban@workflowsimulator.com', '2026-01-30 19:10:47', 'saas', 'Workflow Simulator', 'An AI-powered SaaS that builds a digital twin of an office using 3D visualization and AI agents (plus real users) to simulate, analyze, and optimize team workflows, hiring and training before real-wor', 'Esteban Gallardo', 'https://www.workflowsimulator.com', 'https://youtu.be/2pbE_4iZB54', 'https://www.yourvrexperience.com/courses/spinuoc/Esteban_Gallardo_WorkflowSimulator_CANVAS.pdf', 'https://www.yourvrexperience.com/courses/spinuoc/Esteban_Gallardo_WorkflowSimulator_Resumen_Ejecutivo.pdf', 'Hello, my name is Esteban, and I’m the creator of Workflow Simulator.\n\nWhat is Workflow Simulator?\n\nWorkflow Simulator is an open-source platform that lets companies create a digital twin of their office.\nIt combines project management, 3D visualization, and AI agents to simulate how teams actually work together—before decisions are made in the real world.\n\nWhat problems does it solve?\n\nToday, organizations make critical decisions about workflows, team structures, or hiring based on assumptions, static tools, or trial and error.\nThat leads to inefficiencies, poor onboarding, and costly mistakes.\nWorkflow Simulator provides a safe environment where companies can test workflows, simulate teamwork, and evaluate outcomes—without real-world risk.\n\nWhat is the most innovative feature?\n\nThe key innovation is the AI simulation layer.\nAI agents behave like real team members: they collaborate, attend meetings, manage tasks, and react to changes over time.\nYou can even introduce a real candidate into the simulation and observe soft skills like communication, adaptability, and teamwork—something traditional tools can’t measure.\n\nWho can be interested?\n\nWorkflow Simulator is ideal for startups, HR departments, educators, and innovation teams—anyone who wants to improve collaboration, hiring, training, or project planning using realistic simulations.\n\nWorkflow Simulator is not just a tool—it’s a sandbox for the future of work.\n\nThank you.', 'Hello,\n<p>\nMy name is Esteban Gallardo. I am a computer engineer, and I would like to present my project, <strong>\"Workflow Simulator\"</strong>: a software solution that allows the simulation of a real office environment to carry out work methodology simulations. Its goal is to optimize productive processes, improve recruitment processes, and foster team dynamics and effective leadership.\n</p>\n<p>\n<ol>\n  <li>Video pitch: <a href=\"https://youtu.be/2pbE_4iZB54\">https://youtu.be/2pbE_4iZB54</a></li>\n  <li>Website: <a href=\"https://www.workflowsimulator.com\">https://www.workflowsimulator.com</a></li>\n</ol>\n</p>\n<p>\nOther featured projects (aligned with the proposals above):\n</p>\n<p>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Story Book Editor:</strong> A tool designed to help independent writers convert their works into audiobooks.</li>\n  <li><strong>Applied Technopedagogy:</strong> As part of the Master’s Degree in Technopedagogical Education (UOC), I develop courses based on technopedagogical criteria to maximize learning outcomes through the integration of digital tools.</li>\n</ol>\n</p>\n<p>\nExamples:\n</p>\n<p>\n<ol>\n  <li>Building a Professional Portfolio Website with GitHub Pages & AI: \n    <a href=\"https://www.yourvrexperience.com/learn-to-build-a-professional-portfolio-website-with-github-pages-artificial-intelligence/\">\n      https://www.yourvrexperience.com/learn-to-build-a-professional-portfolio-website-with-github-pages-artificial-intelligence/\n    </a>\n  </li>\n  <li>Learn to Build a Multiplayer VR Game with Unity & VRChat: \n    <a href=\"https://www.yourvrexperience.com/2026/01/11/learn-to-build-a-multiplayer-vr-game-with-unity-vrchat/\">\n      https://www.yourvrexperience.com/2026/01/11/learn-to-build-a-multiplayer-vr-game-with-unity-vrchat/\n    </a>\n  </li>\n</ol>\n</p>\n<p>\nBest regards,\n</p>\n<p>\nEsteban Gallardo\n</p>', 78, '{\"score\": 78, \"evaluation\": \"Scores by criterion (max 4 each): Value Proposition & Problem Addressed: 4 — Clear problem and differentiated AI-powered digital-twin solution addressing real decision risks. Product & Technical Viability: 4 — Functional platform and operational AI agents claimed, with SaaS architecture and scaling readiness described. Business Model & Monetization: 3 — Multiple monetization paths (subscriptions, usage, enterprise, services) but pricing, unit economics and cost assumptions need validation. Target Market & Customers: 3 — Well-identified segments (startups, HR, education, SMEs) with reasonable early-adopter fits but market sizing/segmentation assumptions are not detailed. Competitive Advantage & Differentiation: 3 — Clear differentiators (realistic simulations, soft-skill assessment, open-source) though some advantages may be replicable and need stronger defensibility. Founding Team: 2 — Technical founder with relevant experience; additional commercial, sales and domain expertise are not described. Maturity Level & Traction: 3 — Functional product and demos exist, but evidence of pilots, paying customers, or measurable user validation is limited. Scalability & Medium-Term Vision: 3 — SaaS and architecture planned for scale; AI cost control and commercial scaling strategies need further elaboration. Overall assessment: a viable early-to-mid stage SaaS with a strong, novel value proposition and an operational prototype, but requiring customer validation, commercial team expansion, and rigorous economics/AI-cost controls to reach scale.\", \"strengths\": [\"Clear, compelling value proposition: digital twin for work processes that reduces real-world risks.\", \"Operational prototype and AI agents already developed according to the documents.\", \"Unique combination of project management, 3D visualization and human+AI simulation.\", \"Open-source core enabling extensibility and community contributions.\", \"Diverse monetization channels (subscriptions, usage-based AI billing, enterprise, services).\"], \"weaknesses\": [\"Founding team appears underspecified beyond the technical founder; limited commercial/sales representation.\", \"Limited evidence of customer pilots, paying customers or measurable market traction.\", \"Business economics (pricing, CAC, LTV, AI cost per simulation) are not detailed.\", \"Competitive defensibility partially asserted but lacking clear IP, network effects, or hard-to-replicate moats.\", \"Operational risks around AI accuracy, simulation validity, data privacy/compliance and cost control are not fully addressed.\"], \"recommendations\": [\"Run structured pilot programs with 3–5 target customers (HR, startups, training institutions) and capture quantitative outcomes (time/cost savings, hiring accuracy, training improvement).\", \"Validate pricing and unit economics: model AI cost per simulation, set usage tiers, and test willingness-to-pay with pilot customers.\", \"Strengthen the team by recruiting business development/commercial lead, customer success, and domain experts in HR/organizational psychology.\", \"Document and harden competitive moats: pursue IP where possible, publish validation studies, and build partnerships with HR platforms or training institutions.\", \"Implement technical controls and monitoring for AI cost, simulation fidelity, and data privacy; prepare enterprise-grade security/compliance artifacts to enable larger deals.\", \"Develop a go-to-market playbook (channels, sales motions, target personas) and prioritize use cases with highest ROI to accelerate early customer acquisition.\"]}', '', '', '[{\"title\": \"FlowOps: Workflow Automation for Small Professional Services Firms\", \"match\": 50, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS platforms focused on improving how teams work, aimed at SME customers, emphasize integrations and templates/best-practices, provide guided onboarding and low-friction adoption, and monetize via subscription tiers.\", \"differences\": [\"Workflow Simulator centers on AI-powered digital twins and controlled simulations of office environments (including 3D visualization and AI agents) to test workflows and assess soft skills; FlowOps focuses on no-code workflow automation and industry-specific templates for professional services.\", \"Workflow Simulator emphasizes behavioral/soft-skill assessment and experimentation with human+AI agents; FlowOps emphasizes operational automation, repeatable processes, and reducing administrative time without autonomous AI decision-making.\", \"Workflow Simulator targets broader use cases (startups, HR, education, SMEs) and offers open-source core and consulting/custom simulation services; FlowOps targets small professional services firms (<20 employees) with plug-and-play templates and simpler integrations.\", \"Workflow Simulator explicitly manages AI usage costs and simulation analytics; FlowOps centers on ease-of-use, compliance and integration with email/calendar/cloud storage rather than immersive simulation or 3D UX.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use Workflow Simulator to validate and stress-test FlowOps workflow templates in realistic simulated office scenarios before deployment.\", \"Co-develop professional-services simulation templates that combine FlowOps automation flows with Workflow Simulator behavioral scenarios for onboarding and compliance training.\", \"Offer bundled pilots where FlowOps implements automation and Workflow Simulator measures employee workflow performance and soft-skill impacts.\", \"Share integration connectors and best-practice libraries so FlowOps users can export workflows to simulation scenarios and import validated process improvements back into FlowOps.\"]}, {\"title\": \"InsightPulse: Customer Feedback Analytics for Product Teams\", \"match\": 35, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS products that apply AI to help organizations make better decisions from behavioral or textual data, emphasize human-in-the-loop workflows, and target product/organizational improvement through actionable insights and traceability.\", \"differences\": [\"InsightPulse focuses on ingesting and analyzing qualitative customer feedback (NLP, theme clustering, traceability to roadmap decisions); Workflow Simulator builds a digital twin to simulate team workflows and assess soft skills and operational outcomes.\", \"InsightPulse\'s primary customers are product teams and SaaS companies; Workflow Simulator targets HR, startups, SMEs, educational institutions and organizational design use cases.\", \"InsightPulse centers on text analytics and decision traceability rather than real-time simulation, 3D visualization, or integrating AI agents into simulated task execution.\", \"InsightPulse emphasizes linking feedback to product roadmaps and tracking decisions over time; Workflow Simulator emphasizes risk-free experimentation with organizational changes before real-world deployment.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate InsightPulse to collect and analyze qualitative feedback from participants after simulations to improve scenario realism and measure perceived outcomes.\", \"Use InsightPulse traceability to connect simulation outcomes and participant feedback to product or training changes, enabling evidence-based iteration.\", \"Combine InsightPulse analytics with Workflow Simulator to provide richer post-simulation reports that blend behavioral metrics and free-text reflections.\", \"Pilot with product teams to simulate new product-development workflows and use InsightPulse to capture stakeholder feedback and link it to roadmap decisions.\"]}, {\"title\": \"EduAdmin Cloud: Administrative Management for Small Training Providers\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS offerings that serve educational/training contexts among other markets, aim to reduce administrative overhead for organizations, emphasize simplicity and fast onboarding for non-technical users, and offer subscription-based pricing with potential add-on modules or services.\", \"differences\": [\"EduAdmin Cloud focuses on course, enrollment, certification, scheduling and compliance management for small training providers; Workflow Simulator provides immersive simulations, AI-driven performance analysis, and soft-skill assessment for teams and training scenarios.\", \"Workflow Simulator is built around AI agents, digital twins and experimentation before real-world changes; EduAdmin is an administrative platform prioritizing record-keeping, reporting and operational workflows without simulation or behavioral AI assessment.\", \"EduAdmin targets small training providers as its core customer; Workflow Simulator targets a broader set including HR departments, startups, SMEs and educational institutions interested in training evaluation and organizational design.\", \"Workflow Simulator includes an open-source core and consulting/custom simulation services; EduAdmin emphasizes modular simplicity and compliance-focused features with fast deployment.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Embed Workflow Simulator modules into EduAdmin as an optional assessment/training add-on so training providers can run simulated scenarios and certify soft-skill outcomes alongside administrative records.\", \"Joint go-to-market pilots with vocational and training centers where EduAdmin handles admin workflows and Workflow Simulator provides practical assessment and simulated practice environments.\", \"Integrate certification and reporting outputs from Workflow Simulator into EduAdmin’s certificate issuance and compliance reports to provide evidence-based credentials.\", \"Co-create packaged offerings for training providers that combine administration, scheduling and simulated assessment for blended learning and workforce upskilling programs.\"]}]', '[{\"title\": \"MindAnchor: Evidence-Based Mental Health Support for Young Adults\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both are SaaS platforms focused on human behaviour and wellbeing in institutional contexts (education, employers). Both prioritize ethical positioning, evidence-informed analysis of human interaction, and partnerships with educational institutions and HR. Each offers guided programs and potential for blended human+AI support.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain focus: MindAnchor targets individual mental wellbeing while Workflow Simulator focuses on team workflows and organisational decisions.\", \"Regulatory profile: MindAnchor must operate within clinical/health ethics and GDPR boundaries more strictly.\", \"Product form: MindAnchor is programmatic CBT modules; Workflow Simulator is an interactive digital twin with 3D simulation and AI agents.\", \"Target customer: MindAnchor is D2C and institutional wellbeing buyers vs Workflow Simulator’s emphasis on startups, HR teams, and training organisations.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate short mental-wellbeing micro-modules from MindAnchor into Workflow Simulator scenarios to measure impact on team performance and stress responses.\", \"Co-run pilots with universities or SMEs where MindAnchor users join Workflow Simulator team exercises to validate cross-platform outcomes.\", \"Share anonymized behavioural metrics to improve MindAnchor’s detection of stress in collaborative contexts and to enrich Workflow Simulator’s soft-skill assessment models.\"]}, {\"title\": \"CareLink Home: Coordinated Support for Elderly People Living Alone\", \"match\": 25, \"similarities\": \"Both are platforms that coordinate human actors, emphasize dignity and human-in-the-loop decision-making, and target institutional buyers (municipalities/HR departments). Each values consent, transparency and multi-stakeholder dashboards for operations.\", \"differences\": [\"Domain and users: CareLink Home focuses on eldercare, IoT sensors and emergencies; Workflow Simulator models office teams and collaboration workflows.\", \"Data types: CareLink relies on sensor/time-series and privacy-preserving alerts; Workflow Simulator uses interaction logs, tasks, meetings and simulated agents.\", \"Business model: CareLink is B2G/service-contract heavy; Workflow Simulator is SaaS with tiered subscriptions and consulting.\", \"Intervention model: CareLink prioritizes low-intrusion monitoring and human follow-up; Workflow Simulator enables experimentation and training in virtual environments.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use Workflow Simulator to model and test care-coordination workflows, escalation protocols and multi-actor dashboards before field deployment of CareLink Home.\", \"Run joint pilot to train care coordinators in simulated scenarios (roleplay of emergency response and coordinated follow-up).\", \"Share UX and consent-by-design patterns (human-in-the-loop workflows and transparency design) to improve both platforms’ ethical interfaces.\"]}, {\"title\": \"MoveWell Rehab: Personalized Physical Rehabilitation for Chronic Conditions\", \"match\": 30, \"similarities\": \"Both deliver digital support to improve human performance and adherence, combine professional oversight with scalable digital delivery, and target institutions (clinics, employers, training providers). Both emphasize safe, professional-aligned interventions rather than automated medical decisions.\", \"differences\": [\"Clinical scope: MoveWell focuses on physiotherapy and health outcomes with professional oversight; Workflow Simulator focuses on workplace processes and soft-skill assessment.\", \"Interaction model: MoveWell centers on individual exercise adherence and video guidance; Workflow Simulator centers on multi-person interactions, meetings and organizational tasks.\", \"Regulation and liability: MoveWell has stronger clinical/regulatory constraints and professional accountability.\", \"Technology emphasis: MoveWell emphasizes video and progress-tracking; Workflow Simulator emphasizes AI agents, 3D virtual offices and simulation logic.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Model clinic workflows and patient–clinician handoffs in Workflow Simulator to optimise service delivery and scheduling for MoveWell pilots.\", \"Embed MoveWell’s exercise adherence scenarios inside team simulations to assess how workplace routine affects rehabilitation outcomes and employee return-to-work programs.\", \"Co-develop training modules for physiotherapy clinic staff using simulated patient flows and resource allocation scenarios.\"]}, {\"title\": \"PathLearn: Personalized Learning Pathways for Secondary Education\", \"match\": 45, \"similarities\": \"Both target educational institutions and training contexts, use AI as decision support rather than replacement, and emphasize teacher/facilitator-in-the-loop design. Both provide analytics to improve human performance and learning outcomes and are SaaS platforms oriented to institutional adoption.\", \"differences\": [\"Target user: PathLearn focuses on secondary students and classroom differentiation; Workflow Simulator focuses on adult teams, organizational structure, and workflows.\", \"Use case: PathLearn adapts learning sequences and assessments; Workflow Simulator simulates multi-agent operational scenarios and soft-skill interactions.\", \"Pedagogical model: PathLearn uses mastery learning and formative assessment; Workflow Simulator uses simulated role-play and behavioural observation for hiring/training.\", \"Regulatory/market: PathLearn is B2G/B2B school-centric with curriculum alignment; Workflow Simulator targets HR, startups, SMEs and consulting clients.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Integrate workplace-oriented learning pathways from PathLearn into Workflow Simulator for vocational tracks or career-oriented classroom projects.\", \"Pilot joint educational programs at universities or vocational schools combining PathLearn’s curriculum with Workflow Simulator scenarios to prepare students for team-based work.\", \"Share insights on teacher/facilitator-in-the-loop design to improve simulation debrief workflows and educator dashboards.\"]}, {\"title\": \"SkillBridge: Practice-Based Digital Training for Workforce Reskilling\", \"match\": 70, \"similarities\": \"High overlap: both aim to make workplace skills measurable through practice and simulation, target employers and training institutions, use competency-based assessment, and combine digital platforms with human feedback. Both monetize via B2B contracts, subscriptions and training services.\", \"differences\": [\"Primary approach: SkillBridge focuses on project-based, demonstrable competency via real tasks; Workflow Simulator uses immersive digital twin simulations of team workflows and behavioural interactions.\", \"Feature set: SkillBridge emphasizes submission/evaluation of real projects and rubrics; Workflow Simulator emphasizes AI agents, 3D office environments and soft-skill behaviour analytics.\", \"Partner network: SkillBridge leans on industry co-design and mentor networks; Workflow Simulator emphasizes AI integrations and open-source extensibility.\", \"Outcome focus: SkillBridge measures job-ready competencies; Workflow Simulator measures operational efficiency, decision impacts and soft skills in simulated contexts.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Embed SkillBridge’s competency rubrics as evaluation metrics inside Workflow Simulator scenarios so learners demonstrate job-relevant behaviours within simulated teams.\", \"Co-design reskilling pilots with employers where SkillBridge supplies industry tasks and Workflow Simulator creates realistic team contexts for assessment.\", \"Develop joint enterprise offerings: combined simulation-based assessment + practice-based certification for reskilling programs.\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReadTogether: Inclusive Literacy Support for Early Learners\", \"match\": 20, \"similarities\": \"Both serve educational institutions and training contexts and aim to improve human skills through digital platforms. Each values pedagogical grounding and partnerships with schools and communities.\", \"differences\": [\"Age group and pedagogy: ReadTogether focuses on early literacy (children 5–8) with family engagement and phonics; Workflow Simulator targets adult workforce behaviours and organisational design.\", \"Assessment style: ReadTogether avoids algorithmic grading and emphasizes family-led practice; Workflow Simulator automates performance analysis via AI.\", \"Product form: ReadTogether is content- and audio-focused; Workflow Simulator is a simulation engine with 3D visualisation and AI agents.\", \"Channels and buyers: ReadTogether is school/community-led with grant funding; Workflow Simulator targets startups, SMEs and HR buyers.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use Workflow Simulator to create teacher and admin training scenarios for implementing ReadTogether programs at scale (logistics, classroom routines).\", \"Co-run pilots in schools to model staff workflows and family engagement processes that support ReadTogether adoption.\", \"Exchange expertise on low-friction onboarding and family/community engagement best practices for educational pilots.\"]}, {\"title\": \"LocalHands: Community-Based Support for Informal Caregivers\", \"match\": 25, \"similarities\": \"Both are platform-based initiatives that coordinate multiple human actors, emphasize dignity and community support, and seek partnerships with municipalities and social organizations. Both value facilitation, training and ongoing onboarding.\", \"differences\": [\"Primary mission: LocalHands focuses on peer support and community facilitation for informal caregivers; Workflow Simulator models workplace teams, training and hiring decisions.\", \"Operational model: LocalHands blends local facilitation and non-profit funding models; Workflow Simulator is commercial SaaS with consulting and enterprise licensing.\", \"Tech needs: LocalHands emphasizes community tools and moderation; Workflow Simulator needs simulation engine, AI agent integrations and visualisation.\", \"Target metrics: LocalHands measures caregiver wellbeing and community outcomes vs Workflow Simulator’s operational and soft-skill performance metrics.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Simulate care coordination workflows and escalation scenarios in Workflow Simulator to train local facilitators and test platform features before field pilots.\", \"Develop joint training modules where community facilitators role-play using simulated cases to improve response and coordination.\", \"Share moderation, onboarding and community-engagement design principles to improve retention and ethical safeguards.\"]}, {\"title\": \"AccessPath: Inclusive Employment Pathways for People with Disabilities\", \"match\": 40, \"similarities\": \"Both address hiring, onboarding and workplace inclusion, work with employers and public employment services, and emphasize co-design/ human-centred approaches. Both provide tools to improve retention and job fit and target B2B/B2G contracts.\", \"differences\": [\"Co-creation emphasis: AccessPath centres people with disabilities leading role-design and accommodations; Workflow Simulator focuses on simulating workplaces and measuring general team dynamics.\", \"Service model: AccessPath is advisory and facilitation-heavy; Workflow Simulator is a simulation platform with AI analytics and customizable virtual environments.\", \"Outcomes measured: AccessPath measures job retention and accommodation effectiveness; Workflow Simulator measures workflow efficiency, collaboration and soft skills.\", \"User profiles: AccessPath involves deeper accessibility and legal accommodation processes.\"], \"collaboration\": [\"Use Workflow Simulator to create simulated on-the-job scenarios that test proposed accommodations and role adaptations before real-world placement.\", \"Co-develop onboarding simulations and employer training modules to sensitize teams and validate inclusive workflows.\", \"Integrate AccessPath’s co-design templates into Workflow Simulator’s scenario builder to capture candidate-defined needs and measure impact.\"]}, {\"title\": \"ReLoop Materials: Circular Packaging for Lo